# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Misconceptions
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:misconception-romans-allowed-prasutagus-boudica-rule
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All Romans allowed Prasutagus and Boudica rule the east of England."@en ;
  curric:correction """When Prasutagus died, the Roman Emperor Nero did not want to share power and control of the land with Boudica and her daughters."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.675615Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-england-defeated-spain
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think England defeated Spain easily with their Navy."@en ;
  curric:correction """It was a combination of factors that allowed England to defeat Spain including being helped by the weather."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.675719Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-because-european-seafarers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think because European seafarers were using the navigation tools, they invented them too."""@en ;
  curric:correction """European seafarers didn't invent the astrolabe or compass. Many ancient people navigated by the stars like the Polynesians and Vikings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676045Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-oceans-totally-distinct
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that the oceans are totally distinct, separate bodies of water."@en ;
  curric:correction """Large bodies of water like oceans and seas are connected by smaller bodies of water like rivers. You can sail from one ocean to another."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676102Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-anglo-saxons-one-king-britain
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Anglo-Saxons only had one king in Britain."@en ;
  curric:correction "The Anglo-Saxons had different kingdoms in Britain, each with its own king."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676117Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-past-ships-carried
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that in the past ships only carried sailors, captains or other people working on the ship."""@en ;
  curric:correction """About 200 years ago, people began to travel through choice. People that travel on ships but do not work on them are called passengers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676127Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-inside-places-like-inside-boats
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Inside places (like inside boats) are warmer than outside places."@en ;
  curric:correction """Inside places have shelter from rain, so they're drier, but not necessarily warmer. If a place is cold, everywhere is cold unless heated."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676159Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-believe-victorian-children-worked
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may believe that all Victorian children worked, or that no Victorian children had an education."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Children from wealthy families were educated at home or sent to schools that were paid for. Some children went to small local schools on some days of the week and worked on other days. Some of the least fortunate children did not go to school at all."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676173Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-athelstan-controlled-scotland
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that Athelstan controlled Scotland because he defeated Constantine."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although Constantine lost, Athelstan only remained king of England. He became overlord of Scotland but failed to unite England and Scotland under one kingship."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676184Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-assume-people-able-take
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may assume that people have always been able to take photographs."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that photography was invented 200 years ago and, before that, photographs did not exist. People would have drawn or painted to record what they could see in front of them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676417Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-suleiman-lawgiver-suleiman-magnificent
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some may think that 'Suleiman the Lawgiver' and 'Suleiman the Magnificent' are different people."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that these are different names used for the same person to remember different elements of his time as Sultan of the Ottoman Empire."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676421Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-mediterranean-single-country
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that the Mediterranean is a single country."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Mediterranean is a large area surrounding and including the Mediterranean Sea. Many countries are part of this area."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676473Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-eleanor-louis-married-long
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that Eleanor and Louis were not married for very long."@en ;
  curric:correction """Eleanor and Louis were married for 15 years before their marriage was annulled by the church."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676534Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-emperor-jah-ng
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think Emperor Jahāngīr was angry with Nūr Jahān for becoming powerful."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to pupils that Emperor Jahāngīr admired Nūr Jahān and was grateful to her for looking after him and taking care of his responsibilities while he was ill."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676539Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-second-world-war-happening-1950s
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Second World War was happening in the 1950's."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to the children that the Second World War ended half way through the 1940's. In the 1950's people and cities were recovering from the effects of the war. New houses, technology and transport was available."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676702Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-inventions-things-like-machines-robots
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That inventions are always things like machines, robots, computers and so on."@en ;
  curric:correction """Inventions come from ideas, and people can have ideas about so many different situations in life. The invention here for example is a type of pain relief for childbirth, a medical invention."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676803Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-snakes-used-live-ireland
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That snakes used to live in Ireland."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that snakes were unlikely to have ever lived in Ireland due to the geography and climate. It is thought that the snakes in the story of St. Patrick and the snakes of Ireland were a metaphor or symbol."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676913Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-st-patrick-irish
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That St. Patrick was Irish."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to children that St. Patrick was born in Britain. As a teenager, he was captured by raiders and taken to Ireland."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676918Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-one-legend-boudica
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think there can only be one legend about Boudica."@en ;
  curric:correction """There are many legends about Boudica's death. Historians from the past have told different stories but we do not know which is the truth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.677029Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-legends-true
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That legends are true."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure children understand that legends are stories that are often told verbally and may change over time. Play a game to demonstrate this; children sit in a circle and pass a message around by whispering to each other. Does the messgae change?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.677036Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-robert-bruce-fictional-character-story
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Robert the Bruce is a fictional character in a story."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure that children understand that Robert the Bruce was a real person from the past."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.677157Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-south-africa-refers-southern-half
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That 'South Africa' refers to the southern half of the continent of Africa."@en ;
  curric:correction """'South Africa' is one single African country, which is located in the south of the continent of Africa. The south of africa (the part that sits in the southern hemisphere) covers a much larger area and includes 15 other individual African countries."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.677316Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confused-emperor-20-wives
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may be confused by the emperor having 20 wives."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to pupils that in some countries and some religions you can marry multiple people. However today in the UK, it is illegal to marry more than one person."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.677433Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-welsh-lords-chanting-owain-glyndwr
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Welsh lords were chanting 'Owain Glyndwr, Prince of Wales' because he was the Prince."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure children know that the Welsh lords were chanting because they wanted Owain to become the Prince of Wales and their leader."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.677676Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-assume-people-past-used
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may assume that people in the past used phones and tablets to take photographs."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Show pupils the various devices that have been used in the past to take photographs and how they have evolved."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.677711Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-fact-united-kingdom
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils can struggle with the fact that the United Kingdom is a country made up of four separate smaller countries. Furthermore we also refer to Great Britain - which can again be confusing for pupils."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The UK's full name is The United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland. England, Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland make up the UK. Great Britain is only the mainland countries of England, Wales and Scotland that share land borders."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.677740Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-life-same-750-years-ago
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That life was the same 750 years ago as it is today."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to children that lots of things were very different 750 years ago. For example, there were no cars, planes or trains and it would have taken Owain a long time to travel to Scotland and London. People would have travelled by horse or walked."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.677744Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-photographs-way-find-1960s-1970s
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That photographs are the only way to find out about the 1960s and 1970s."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that photographs are one source that historians can use. They also look at written evidence such as newspaper articles and diaries. They can talk to people who were alive in the 1960s and 1970s and look at artefacts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.677827Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-failure-capture-vienna-meant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that the failure to capture Vienna meant Suleiman was a failure."@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise that setbacks are normal and Suleiman was still able to extend the Ottoman Empire to its greatest ever reach."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.677870Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-church-same-church-building
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that the Church is the same as a church building."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Church is the name of the organisation that includes all the people who lead the Christian religion. Buildings are also called churches."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.677895Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-johns-sisters-line-throne
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that John's sisters would be in line to the throne before him."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that this is the case today in the UK - Princess Charlotte became the first female royal to benefit from The Succession to the Crown Act in 2013. The Act stated that girls born into the Royal Family will not be overtaken by younger brothers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.677927Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-families-same-140-years-ago
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That all families were the same 140 years ago and life was the same for everyone."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that while the photograph gives us some clues to life in the past, just like now, all families were different."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.678038Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-classes-society-small
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that classes in society are small groups, like classes at school."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Classes are groups of people, but classes in society include thousands, sometimes millions of people and they are not age related like school classes, they depend on other factors like wealth or profession."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.678043Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-kings-queens-king-john
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that kings and queens after King John forgot about Magna Carta."@en ;
  curric:correction """Kings and queens after King John still followed Magna Carta and it remained as a very important document of rights for the people. Today, there are still four of the original 63 clauses in use in England."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.678114Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-term-caravan
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may confuse the term caravan."@en ;
  curric:correction "Explain to pupils that a group of camels is called a caravan."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.678121Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-musa-keita-meant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think Musa Keita was meant to be mansa."@en ;
  curric:correction """Musa Keita became mansa because the previous mansa did not return from his voyage and he chose Musa Keita to replace him."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.678126Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-kings-queens-needed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think all kings and queens needed to be married."@en ;
  curric:correction """Elizabeth decided she didn’t want to marry and she proved that she didn’t need to be to be a successful queen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.678266Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-names-aethelflaed-aethelred-similar-mistaken
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The names Aethelflaed and Aethelred are very similar and may be mistaken for the same person."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Highlight that the two names are very similar but that Aethelflaed was the daughter of Alfred the Great and became Lady of Mercia, whereas Aethelred was the king of the Anglo-Saxon kingdom of Mercia."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.678626Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-aquitaine-same-modern-day
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that Aquitaine is the same as modern day France."@en ;
  curric:correction """Aquitaine was only one area of modern day France, there were lots of areas controlled by different powerful families at this time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.678698Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-buildings-commissioned-suleiman-used
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some may think that the buildings commissioned by Suleiman are not used or in existence today."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Many of them still exist 500 years later and can be seen today, particularly the mosques and religious buildings which have been continually renovated over time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.678825Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-britain-still-rules
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that Britain still rules over or controls India today."@en ;
  curric:correction """Britain does not rule India today. Britain ruled India and much of the surrounding land for over 300 years, but this ended in 1947 when the territory was partitioned into two separate independent countries which became India and Pakistan."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.678894Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-muslims-pilgrimage
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think all Muslims have to do the pilgrimage."@en ;
  curric:correction """The pilgrimage is something many Muslims would like to do. However, it is only required if they are able to do it. Travelling to Mecca is too expensive for many people. Others might not be physically able to do the pilgrimage."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679527Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-mehr-al-nes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think Mehr al-Nesā sitting next to a snake is completely true."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to the pupils that Mehr al-Nesā's early life is still unknown. There are only legends about her story. A legend is a traditional story that might not always be true."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679532Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-elizabeth-born-queen
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that Elizabeth was born a queen."@en ;
  curric:correction """There was already a king and queen in throne. There cannot be more than one king and queen at a time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679694Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-change-elizabeths-education-became-heir
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There was no change in Elizabeth's education after she became an heir and she continued as she was."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Reinforce the events before and after this significant turning point in Elizabeth's life."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679806Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-paul-stephensons-actions-directly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that only Paul Stephenson's actions directly led to the 1965 law."@en ;
  curric:correction "Paul's actions had an impact as did many other people's in the 1960s."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679910Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-militant-tactics-good
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some children might think that militant tactics are a good way for them to get the things that they want to."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The Suffragettes used extreme tactics because they felt that it was their only option. Going on hunger strike is dangerous. For the issues that children might face, there are many safer and less harmful ways to make a change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679914Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-archbishop-canterbury-part
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that the Archbishop of Canterbury is a part of the royal family."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Reinforce the fact that the Archbishop of Canterbury works with the royal family and is also very important, but is not related."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679983Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-women-allowed-go-university
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some may think that women were not allowed to go to university at all in Victorian Britain."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Women were allowed to study at university, work very hard and take all of the same exams as men, but they were not allowed the degree at the end of it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680193Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-assume-elizabeth-going-heir
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may assume that Elizabeth was always going to be an heir."@en ;
  curric:correction "The abdication had to happen in order for Elizabeth to be an heir."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680209Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-emily-davison-quit-her
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that Emily Davison quit her job to join the Suffragettes."@en ;
  curric:correction """Emily joined the Suffragettes in 1906 and did not quit her job to fight for women's suffrage full time until 1908."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680214Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-coronation-ceremony-person-becomes-monarch
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That a coronation ceremony is when a person becomes a monarch."@en ;
  curric:correction """The person who is first in line to the throne becomes monarch the minute that the previous monarch passes away. It happens in an instant. The coronation is an official ceremony, held later where the monarch receives their crown in front of people."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680237Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-zheng-went-his
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that Zheng He went on his voyages by himself."@en ;
  curric:correction """He was admiral of the Chinese fleet. He took many ships and lots of sailors on the voyages."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680242Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-impression-vikings-fierce-scary
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may have the impression that all Vikings were fierce, scary warriors."@en ;
  curric:correction """Some Vikings were warriors, but not all. Vikings were also traders, farmers and settlers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680286Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-looking-2d-map-world-pupils
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When looking at a 2D map of the world, pupils may think that there are two Pacific oceans."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The Pacific Ocean is the biggest ocean on earth. We can see on a globe that it is one large body of water between the Americas and Asia."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680295Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-archaeologists-dig-bones
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that archaeologists only dig up bones, like dinosaurs or extinct creatures."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Archaeologists work with all sorts of objects from the past, many of the items in museums have been dug up by an archaeologist."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680341Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-emily-davison-paul-stephenson
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some may think that Emily Davison and Paul Stephenson were fighting for the same thing."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emily Davison and Paul Stephenson were fighting for different change to happen in Britain at different times, around 50 years apart."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680372Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-evacuation-negative-experience-children
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That evacuation was a negative experience for all children."@en ;
  curric:correction """Lots of children had healthier diets, more freedom and enjoyed their lives in the countryside."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680461Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-adults-worked-jobs
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that only adults worked at jobs in factories in Victorian times."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In Victorian times, there were no laws stopping children working. Children had to earn money to live, so many of them worked in factories. Since they were young and small, children were useful for getting into tight spaces to clean or fix machines."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680502Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-soon-someone-arrested-go
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that as soon as someone is arrested, they go to prison."@en ;
  curric:correction """This doesn't happen and is not what happened to Paul Stephenson. He was kept in a holding cell in the police station until midnight."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680674Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-people-came-britain-caribbean
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that people only came to Britain from the Caribbean."@en ;
  curric:correction """People from all over the world came to Britain, including from places like India and Poland."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680951Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-emily-davison-died-day
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that Emily Davison died on the day of the Epsom Derby."@en ;
  curric:correction "Emily Davison died four days after the race at Epsom, on the 8th of June 1913."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680956Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-elizabeth-fought-actively
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that Elizabeth fought actively during the war."@en ;
  curric:correction "She contributed remotely but played a role that was just as pivotal."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681939Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-certain-jobs-men-women
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That certain jobs are for men only or women only."@en ;
  curric:correction "Just like during the war, anyone should be able to and can do any job."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682033Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-eleanor-prisoner-kept-terrible
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think of Eleanor as a prisoner being kept in terrible conditions."@en ;
  curric:correction """Eleanor lived in places of comfort, for example, castles. She did not have the freedom to leave but was well looked after."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682401Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-relics-st-columba
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think the relics of St Columba were valuable."@en ;
  curric:correction """The relics of St Columba were an important symbol of the Christian faith throughout the kingdom of Alba."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682440Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-trains-same-victorian-times-today
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Trains were the same in the Victorian times as today."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that the trains in the Victorian times were run on steam. They would have been very dirty, noisy and bumpy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682536Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-crystal-palace-still
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that the Crystal Palace is still standing or that it can be seen or visited today."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The Crystal Palace was a temporary structure built for the exhibition. It was relocated and rebuilt in another part of London but was later destroyed by fire. The surrounding area was then named Crystal Palace to show how important the structure was."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682543Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-victoria-albert-married-because-made
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That Victoria and Albert only married because they were made to do so, not because they loved each other."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Victoria and Albert had a strong connection from the first time they met. Written evidence tells us that the two were very much in love and their marriage was a happy, loving relationship."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682549Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-elizabeth-right-throne
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think Elizabeth had a right to the throne when her father Henry VIII died."""@en ;
  curric:correction """At this time, the heir to the throne was the first-born son of the King rather than the first-born child."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682554Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-queen-victoria-died-queen-elizabeth
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That when Queen Victoria died, then Queen Elizabeth II became queen."@en ;
  curric:correction """There were other monarchs in between Queen Victoria and Queen Elizabeth II. Queen Elizabeth II was the next female monarch but she did not become queen until 50 years after Queen Victoria died."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682581Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-revenge-involves-killing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think revenge always involves killing people."@en ;
  curric:correction """Revenge is the act of getting back at someone for something they did to you. This may involve stealing something or destroying something like property."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682666Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-women-able-lead
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think women were not able to lead rebellions."@en ;
  curric:correction """Boudica was a strong leader and the tribes respected her. The tribes were happy to follow her as part of the rebellion against the Romans."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682689Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-polynesia-country
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that Polynesia is a country."@en ;
  curric:correction """Polynesia is not one single country. It is a large area of the Pacific Ocean containing lots of different islands."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686793Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-chinese-ships-engines
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Chinese ships must have had engines."@en ;
  curric:correction """Engines had not been invented yet. Chinese sailing ships relied on the wind and power of the sea to make long journeys."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687167Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-race-across-atlantic
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that the 'race across the Atlantic' was an actual race, like on school sports day."""@en ;
  curric:correction """At around the same time, people in different places were trying to achieve the same thing, so whoever achieved it first won the 'race'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687189Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-ship-called-fighting-temeraire
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that the ship was called 'The Fighting Temeraire'."@en ;
  curric:correction """'The Fighting Temeraire' was the name of Turner's painting, the ship was called HMS Temeraire."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687247Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-find-confusing-john-cabot
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might find it confusing that John Cabot sounds like a very English name yet he was Italian."""@en ;
  curric:correction """John Cabot is the English version of the name he was born as, Giovanni Caboto. He lived in England for so long he was known by John Cabot."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687279Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-explorers-use-map
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that explorers always use a map."@en ;
  curric:correction """Early explorers did not have maps. They often used natural features to navigate by such as rivers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687324Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-believe-elizabeth-queen-england
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may believe that Elizabeth was only queen of England."@en ;
  curric:correction "Reinforce that she was queen of four nations - the United Kingdom."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690113Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-malta-close-uk
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that Malta is close to the UK."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to pupils how long it would take to travel there in the past (by boat) and today (by air)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695915Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-nothing-known-victoria-indeed-other
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That nothing is known about Victoria (or indeed other monarchs) before becoming Queen."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There is a lot of historical evidence about Victoria's childhood including written accounts and artefacts that tell us a great deal about what her early life was like."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696779Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-get-confused-britain-united
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may get confused between Britain and United Kingdom."@en ;
  curric:correction """Reinforce that Britain is the landmass where the three countries of England, Wales and Scotland are located."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700494Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-princess-anne-queen
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that Princess Anne would be queen after Elizabeth."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that it is the eldest child who inherits the throne and therefore Charles, Prince of Wales, became King of England."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.701796Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-thousands-people-attend-funerals
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that thousands of people attend funerals usually."@en ;
  curric:correction """Emily Davison's funeral was an exception. Usually funerals are only attended by people who knew the person."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.703911Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-people-allowed-work-bristol
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some may think that the only people not allowed to work for the Bristol bus companies in 1963 were black people."""@en ;
  curric:correction "The bus companies did not allow anyone who was not white to work for them."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.704698Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-elizabeth-queen-whilst-king-george
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Elizabeth was queen whilst King George VI was alive because she took on some responsibilities."""@en ;
  curric:correction """King George VI was still alive and therefore still king. It is only after his death that she became queen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.704954Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confused-archbishop-canterbury-leader
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may be confused that the Archbishop of Canterbury is the leader of the Church of England."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Teach pupils that Elizabeth was symbolically the governor of the Church of England and the coronation emphasised this."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.705946Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-philip-prince-greece-denmark
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Philip was always the Prince of Greece and Denmark."@en ;
  curric:correction "Philip gave up his titles in 1947 so that he could marry Princess Elizabeth."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707309Z"^^xsd:dateTime .
